06110nam a22009735i 9783839447628DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020408862  a97838394476287 a10.14361/97838394476282doi  a(DE-B1597)515727  a(OCoLC)1121055439  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aInternet AccessbAEU 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a0001 aBens, Jonas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Affective Societies :bAn Interdisciplinary Essay /cGabriel Scheidecker, Gerhard Thonhauser, Nur Yasemin Ural, Dina Wahba, Robert Walter-Jochum, M. Ragip Zik, Hans Roth, Friederike Oberkrome, Matthias Lüthjohann, Hauke Lehmann, Antje Kahl, Thomas John, Jonas Bens, Aletta Diefenbach. 1aBielefeld : btranscript Verlag, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEmotionsKulturen / EmotionCultures ;v700tFrontmatter -- tEditorial -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction: The Politics of Affective Societies -- t2. Making Things Public and Private: The Affective Co-Production of the Political Sphere -- t3. Conflict and Consent: The Political Ambivalences of Affect and Emotions -- t4. Judgment and Contestation: The Affective Life of Norms -- t5. Conclusions: Affective Societies and the Political -- tBibliography -- tList of Authors0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aMany recent academic and semi-academic voices claim that political deliberation has become exceedingly affective and hence destabilizing. Approaching the question from a wide range of angles, the authors of this interdisciplinary essay remain sceptical that it is really increased affectivity that constitutes the symptom of our times. They propose instead to reframe the debate by deploying the analytic of affective societies - claiming that affect and emotion are in fact present in all social interaction. What changes over time and place are not, then, the absence or presence of affect and emotions, but rather the modes and calibrations of affective and emotional registers. In this manner, this essay works towards a theory of affect and the political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSocial sciences (General). 4aAffect. 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCultural Theory. 4aCulture. 4aEmotion. 4aEthnology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh  aAffect.  aCultural Anthropology.  aCultural Studies.  aCultural Theory.  aCulture.  aEmotion.  aEthnology.1 aDiefenbach, Aletta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJohn, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLehmann, Hauke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLüthjohann, Matthias, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOberkrome, Friederike, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRoth, Hans, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aScheidecker, Gabriel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aThonhauser, Gerhard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aUral, Nur Yasemin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWahba, Dina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWalter-Jochum, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aZik, M. Ragip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z9